Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth U.S. president of history.
The diploma, medal and cheque of $1.4 million will receive them, inter alia, for the exceptional effort in strengthening global diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will reach the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and they will have a lot to do.
First, he visited the Nobel Institute, where he first met with the five members of the committee who, in October, chose him from 172 people to 33 organizations.
Then, the presidential couple scheduled a meeting with the king of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon the visit will culminate with a ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive it, although the third president to receive it in his position.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the prize, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President does not wish to avoid this issue, knowing that he is receiving the prize as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts increased further with the dispatch of additional troops to Afghanistan, which does not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, the diploma and the cheque of ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million Czech crowns).
It is proposed to give them charitable paraphins, but it has not yet decided to which particular organization.
During his full programme, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet to which, in addition to the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests will attend.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude toward the prize.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling that he did not deserve it at all.
He repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for all who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action".
