A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in ‘embedded’ HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists tests new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some medicines already accessible.
AIDS cannot be cured until now.
However, the lives of patients can be significantly extended through a mix of medicines that prevent replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; drugs no longer work against them.
The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarborans have an effect on the albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way to all the medicines used today, and therefore can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
Metalocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedra cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are united by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A Traitor and Resistant Virus
HIV Protease is an HIV virus albumin, and it is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, HIV fractionation does not occur and mature and infectious body cells of the virus will not be created.
