Gradual relief
Composed of the country's constitution in 1978, the policy of a single son of China is possibly the most controversial mandate introduced to date by the Communist Party.
Couples who violate politics face enormous fines, up to three times their annual salary in some areas, and labour discrimination.
Chinese officials have endorsed the policy for its contribution to avoid critical pressure on their natural resources, while human rights defenders have denounced abuses in the imposition of politics.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to undergo abortions.
