A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, which has so far been characterized by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, gained renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a timeless negotiation, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Elaborated by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not speak of how much money the rich countries would give to the poor to face global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, which include how developed economies and key emerging economies would cut down on their coal production, and what would be the limit of the global temperature increase that political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives him a lot of flexibility in the process, said John Coequyt, a senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summed up a 180-page negotiation text to focus on what the top UN climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the great panorama."
It shows profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut emissions by 2020 by between 25 and 45 per cent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also stimulated the talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
However, Friday presented the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated the talks last week.
The United States special climate envoy Todd Stern rejected statements requesting mandatory cuts in greenhouse gas emissions to industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China, with respect to what the Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make an agreement without the major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after China's Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs He Yafei stated that the U.S.'s ultimate climate negotiator lacked "common sense," or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the United States would not help China economically to face global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's main powers at stake, the failure lines have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The present battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries of the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the main powers are discussing who should cost the expenses to limit greenhouse gases, even when vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in seeking to contain the large issuers responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, Ulate maintained, who also works as regional advisor on climate change in Mexico and Central America, for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most major participants said that talks would bring about political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, drafted a proposal for a preliminary treaty of 24 pages early in the morning of Friday.
Artur Runge-Metzger, leading international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the thrust of small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and require action by emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency while delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues must be resolved before the heads of government come to an end.
High-level officials, such as the Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister, descended from the planes and ran to Bella Center corridors, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, in order to delimit the complaints that will be arbitrarily made during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (on which every day 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center, guitar-playing activists present night shows mocking the countries that they believe are being sold, and hand-in-hand preliminary proposals are passed instead of via mail), poses a challenge.
