This means that in this case there will be a process worthy of a saga on one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter dispute the reins of the empire of cosmetics L'Oréal.
However, the Correctional Court No. 15 also ordered Liliane Bettencourt, 87, to undergo a medical examination by three medical professionals.
L'Oréal's heir and principal shareholder always refused to submit to such examinations, even more so under the conditions proposed by the Nanterre Prosecutor's Office during the investigation.
Physicians designated on Friday will be required to report by March 10, 2010, in which they will have to record whether Liliane Bettencourt suffered from states of weakness and during what periods.
I think he'll take it.
I'm going to talk to her, said Mrs. Bettencourt's lawyer, Georges Kiejman, on leaving the audience.
For his part, Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' lawyer Olivier Metzner was pleased with the court's decision.
It is an excellent news (...) The expert will show that he (Banier) manipulated this old lady, whom we must protect, he said.
For two years, Liliane Bettencourt's only daughter began criminal actions against François-Marie Banier, a photographer and multifaceted artist, accusing him of having taken advantage for years of her mother's weakness to obtain a billion euros in donations, through cheques, life insurance contracts or works of art.
For his part, Liliane Bettencourt always refused to have been manipulated by the photographer, whom he considers a long-standing friend.
On Friday, while the court examined the outcome of the action brought by Mrs. Bettencourt-Meyers, the allegations of the lawyers were, on some occasions, a great family confession.
In this way, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer took into account three letters that his client had sent (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to his notary in which he said he mistrusted Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to counsel: "I could explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier between one and two times a day for 15 years.
Since his wedding, I've never been able to speak to Françoise again."
On the other hand, the Office of the Prosecutor of Nanterre considered, once again, that the complainant was not in a position to appear, even more so since a guardianship judge refused, in recent days, to make a request to open a judicial guardianship procedure for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to appear before justice, is not under guardianship and has no guardian.
No other person can appear in his place," said the representative of the Public Prosecutor, Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
Finally, the court decided that the judgment on the admissibility of Mrs Bettencourt-Meyers would be delivered.
Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees to adhere to "values" determined from above as it was previously intended to impose on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave place to the strategies of conquering the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to the customer's preference factors is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and even more, of business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive behaviour and a forward-looking vision"; it requires employees to make a commitment that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian direction.
For this reason, we called for a managerial revolution, which would be to put the partners at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as Orange's questionnaire among its employees, encourage the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all the companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from large engineering schools, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the ancient behavioral theory that the American "neurosciences" reactivated recently, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread behind their backs.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent research of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a position of mechanistic management, inadequate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, implies adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It is about integrating in all reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motiveuntional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company on the basis of a default doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to assess what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate the management of human resources "in place."
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo speech: for the "fair war" Obama receives praise from the right
This Friday, the U.S. right, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of "fair war" against the enemies of the United States, acclaimed Obama's speech on Thursday.
The Conservatives, who had discredited Obama's award on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate during the 2008 elections.
I loved what she said, said Mrs. Palin, the main figure of the right wing of the Republican party to the USA Today newspaper, and added that she herself had addressed the issue of war "sometimes necessary" in her recently published memoirs.
In my opinion, war is, of course, the last thing Americans want to be forced to do, but it is necessary.
Terrorists must be stopped, he observed.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, dedicated himself, this Thursday in Oslo, to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 more soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, considered that the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really good, the former Speaker of the House of Representatives was happy, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential words.
For moments, the speech seemed very historical, said Gingrich, during an interview on the radio program "The Takeaway".
The former elected representative, whom some consider to be a possible candidate for the republican investiture for the 2012 presidential elections, was pleased to hear "a leftist president" when he reminded the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free or could deliver a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
According to Michael Gerson, author of George W. Bush's speeches and current chronicler in the Washington Post, Obama spoke "a very American speech."
In addition to presenting himself as "a citizen of the world", as "he always does", "he spoke as an American president" by reminding Europeans "that they live in a security bubble that they did not create and that they do not do much to preserve it," Gerson said.
Among the few not very convinced right-wing, a hawk of the Bush era, former UN ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "monotonous, pretentious and lacking inspiration" on the National Review Online Internet site.
To the left of the president, Democratic representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When we cover the war with the notion of justice, it is easy to justify the massacre of innocents, he warned.
However, the left centre press praised the president.
Los Angeles Time, while still believing that Obama received the Nobel Prize prematurely, called his "overproduction" speech especially for a speaker known for his talent.
Oslo's speech "should serve as a road map to guide international decisions in the fight against conflict, poverty and oppression," the Californian newspaper said enthusiastically.
Obama "pronounced the discourse that was necessary," said the New York Times, judging him "as both gloomy and uplifting."
