Turkish justice dissolves the prokurd party, a decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled on Friday in favour of the dissolution of the main prokurd party of the country, a decision that immediately provoked demonstrations of anger in the Kurdish community, in the Southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the government's task, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community trying to put an end to 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it had become the "focus of activities that adversely affect the independence of the State and its indivisible unity", the President of the Court, Hasim Kiliz, declared to the press after four days of discussion.
The decision of the 11 judges was unanimous, although only a majority of seven votes were needed to obtain the dissolution, said Kiliz, and added that 37 of the party leaders, including his president Ahmet Türk and Mrs Aysel Tugluk, were excluded from political life for five years.
The judge also announced the cessation of parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of the party's property by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 banks in Parliament (of 550).
Its leaders warned before the verdict that Members would leave Parliament before they became MPs without a partisan label.
The decision follows a procedure launched by the Prosecutor of the Supreme Court, Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, in 2007, which accuses the DTP of obeying the "principles" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many more countries.
Numerous observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party claims that it does not have "organic links" with the PKK, but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The Tribunal's verdict intervenes at the time the government lends a hand to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen its rights, so that the Kurds stop supporting the PKK and thus put an end to the conflict.
DTP leaders said that a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in the Southeast Anatolia, where a large number of demonstrations against the conditions of detention of the PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan degenerated into clashes with the police over the past few weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, thousands of protesters have gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the great city of the Southeast mostly populated by Kurds.
The Order's Forces threw tear grenades and used water cannons, while protesters dropped Molotov bombs or stones with hooligans.
In Istanbul, approximately one hundred people were also concentrated.
Following the verdict, Türk stated that the decision of justice was to "deepen the discouraging."
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurda, NDLR) by dissolving a party, it declared to the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also regrets the decision.
In principle, we oppose the closure of parties.
Thus nothing is resolved, declared the Minister of Energy, Taner Yildiz.
This decision completely boycotts the democratic opening launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK launched an attack in which seven soldiers died three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the bloodiest attacks in recent months.
Snowstorms can begin suddenly
A truly cool winter is what Wolfgang Brauburger wants.
