The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa hallae had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal of two meters long and 1.50 meters high that ran on the two strong rear legs, had an enlarged head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with hoez-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, it would not have been anything special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the Science magazine on Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window towards early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and the characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation in 2006 at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we have found a dozen dinosaur bones on one day, this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a member of the Utah Museum of Natural History team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were gathered in total.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt is an exceptional finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other experts in dinosaurs do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, comments for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, the experts discuss, for example, when the saurios were divided into their three most important genealogical lines: the carnivorous teropods among those found in the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the herbivorous Ornithischia (saurios con pelvis de ave), to which belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt's and his colleagues' analysis, Tawa hallae is a primitive teropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, comments Nesbitt.
For example, in Tawa's skull, researchers found signs of airbags, such as those of the descendants of the terpods, the birds.
Thanks to airbags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa finds also the bones of the spine were evidently filled with partial air.
Tawa is the teropod with older and primitive airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Because the paired line of the later giant sauropods also possessed airbags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups would already produce this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers deduce that the saurios came out there for the first time.
Therefore, the three genealogical lines were separated at the beginning and extended from South America through all corners of the Earth, which at that time was still a unique earthly mass, the Pangea supercontinent.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa find the remains of two other teropods not very closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single parented ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migratory waves were given to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, who belongs to a brother group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says the paleontologist of Bonn Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many fossils of dinosaurs continue to be preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line from reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic the dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosaurus and many other saurios.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs expanded around the world and many new species developed, while the kinship was extinguished at the Triassic limit towards the Jurassic.
Successful Stories Were Not Eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, Martin Sander comments.
A massive extinction could have been given to which dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a brake meteorite impact the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
