New Silicon Valley
For many years, it was considered a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was in the Soviet Union a place heavily guarded for secret investigation of armaments.
Today, the community of 216,000 inhabitants, located 37 kilometres from central Moscow, is considered to be the "Silicon Valley".
Here are important research and production centers for micro and nanoelectronics.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenograd have contacted Riedberg's scientific headquarters in Frankfurt, university institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
Several mutual visits were given and now, on Wednesday, Selenograd and Riedberg sign a "Close Collaboration Protocol" in Frankfurt.
The Deputy Mayor of Moscovita Juri Rosljak and Mayor of Selengrad, Anatoly Smirnov, headed the Russian delegation; Frankfurt signed the planning services chief Edwin Schwarz.
In 2010 they will travel to a seminar in Selenograd representatives of FIZ and managers of small and medium-sized enterprises of the Natural Sciences Research Centre.
Scientific exchange
It is a continuous scientific exchange.
But it also deals with trade relations.
FIZ's companies will have the opportunity to put a foot on the growing Russian market.
In return, Russian scientific companies wish to have access to contracts in Germany.
Selenograd is the headquarters of important Russian research companies and institutes.
Among them are, for example, the Moscow Institute of Electronic Technology, the great Sitronics and Rossijskaja Elektronika consortia.
The community was founded in 1958 as the so-called "Social Planning City" for arms investigation.
Selenograd (literally translated as "Green City") received its name from the landscape of forested mountains, where research facilities settled.
