As with the ABS anti-lock and ESP stability control, emergency braking support systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all new passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a period of deficiency is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, by its way of working, it can also help avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency braking assistant does what it does is to increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the pedestrian that the driver gives.
But this does not always keep that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of Bosch car components, the third part of the drivers involved in an accident had not come to step on the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
