The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car in stopping.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four claims would be avoided with damage to people - when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, as well as acting lightly on the brakes.
